<br />
Helen is Asian. Candice is black. Andy is gay. I'm not even including the 1/16th Cherokee guy who says the stupidest things about Natives and women (he talked about fingering one of the girls in the house, saying he wanted to &quot;check out her meat wallet&quot; to see what he had to work with), just the hardcore racists.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>I reveal who won HoH and who this week's Have Nots are</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
Aaryn won HoH, which gives her the right to dictate who in the house suffers rather uncomfortable penalties all week. Her choices? The woman who got her showmance kicked out of the house (legitimate revenge pick), the gay guy, the black girl, and the Asian girl. 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
<br />
Now the thing that should really have bells and whistles going off for you is this: most of this stuff was not said during the heat of some argument, or to demean someone in the house to their face. This was mostly just &quot;shooting the shit&quot; moments between people chilling in the house, while the people being attacked were not in the room. Candice is the only one who had been in any sort of confrontation with the people saying this crap, so this wasn't even people bonding over a common opponent. This was racists being racist, on a show where everybody knows they're being recorded and watched 24/7. I mean, Jesus, the host of the show is Julie Chen, the wife of the president of CBS, and they're shooting their mouths off about cooking rice and straightening eyes? How dumb do you have to be?<br />
<br />
The reaction from CBS has been interesting. None of these comments have made the show, not any of them. Given that this season's special twist is a power bestowed on players who win a fan vote from week to week, that has some people a little upset. Inside the house, at first production tried talking to the houseguests. At one point last week, when the three above were still saying stupid things, the voice of production came over the loudspeaker and told the houseguests, &quot;Houseguests, just a reminder...&quot; and trailed off. But one of the houseguests shouted out the completion of the sentence, showing that they'd been talked to: &quot;...please don't make racist comments about other houseguests.&quot; So since that wasn't working, maybe two days ago the live feeds were reset, and people noticed that they're now on a five minute delay. The assumption is CBS is going to edit out all the racist comments from the formerly-live feed to avoid the bad press, because they can't get people who depend on production for everything required to live to stop being racist in the house.<br />
<br />
As for the firings: GinaMarie was hired to be a role model to pageant girls. East Coast USA had even told all their girls to watch her on the feeds and vote for her for the special power (MVP). If you're in an organization to be a role model, conduct unbecoming is a very good reason to be terminated. In Aaryn's case, I think it's more a matter of economics. She was removed as a client by her modelling agency. Who is going to book her to represent their company after this? This story spread past the usual tabloids that cover reality TV, and even past the usual groups that monitor and react to racism and homophobia, and hit the mainstream media (like CNN). Aaryn may be very attractive, but she's unbookable.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Philo</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">Heh, there are people who actually watch this crap 24 hours a day and transcribe it all looking for bad language.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>The fans who watch the feeds mostly do it to see gameplay, or (honestly) to catch moments of nudity or sexuality. The feeds also have a flashback feature, where you can go back to any exact time and see what happened. So once someone notices something as shocking as some of this stuff, a flashback time is posted so others can see it. There are people who do summaries of important conversations, or screencaps/videos of funny/interesting/sexy stuff, but I gather the primary way people see this stuff is using the flashback. (I follow the show, and read the summaries/discussions, but don't watch the feeds.)<br />
<br />
BTW - this year's group includes the most attractive set of women the show has ever featured. So if you want a reason to watch, well, there's one. Here's Aaryn:<br />
