		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: 'Big Brother' Racist And Homophobic Comments Get Two Contestants Fired From Day J
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1786779">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							I don't think the players have really figured out the MVP dynamic, so they're all walking on eggshells (although that changes this week). The MVP makes the game fairly straightforward: make an alliance that has numbers overall in the house, then get the MVP to be your alliance's friend. Until MVP shifts, the other side of the house is completely unable to stop you from eliminating them, down to two players (at which point they can save themselves with HoH and Veto)(three if they get very lucky with who plays in and wins veto). This is because the same number of people without votes exists for both sides of the house in the best case scenario - the two nominees versus the HoH and the MVP's nominee. So numbers wins every week with the MVP on board. The MVP can only save themselves from being booted by putting up a more tempting target than themselves, so it's very much in the interests of the MVP to find that big alliance and partner up. Note that the MVP can't save themselves other than by putting up a more tempting target, so the MVP mechanic is perfect for a producer who wants to rig the game to get a certain group to the jury. Convince the group to ally in the diary room, convince one of them to swing the MVP to them (after convincing the MVP to reveal themselves), watch the other side of the house crumble, then the alliance votes out the MVP when they're done.<br />
<br />
The MVP will only shift if the side of the house getting Pagonged has more total fans voting than the current MVP, as presumably the majority of fans will switch voting allegiance to someone in the same alliance if their favourite is voted out. This is what was observed with the Glass House show last summer, where fan voting determined who left the house. Given Elissa's background, how little of the drama she's causing has been shown on the show, and the edit Aaryn got tonight, I would be very surprised if Aaryn's side of the house had enough fans combined to topple Elissa. What Aaryn's people don't seem to get yet is they really don't want to vote Elissa out. They need to flip her to their side. If they vote her out, MVP will pass to someone else who is determined to get them out of the house, and they won't know who it is to target them for elimination. Elissa made noise early in the season about an all-female alliance, and if she's anything like her sister she's a sucker for people apologizing, so the door is open to flipping things around.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Destructis</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">To be honest, this group is pretty boring.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Many of them are. There's too much hush-hush and walking on eggshells right now for anything exciting to happen (although I'll tell you now, there's at least one shouting match this week that should make the show). I &quot;watch&quot; Big Brother After Dark: I fast-forward unless I see something interesting or unless I see Kaitlin on camera. Recently, I've added Amanda to the &quot;will stop and watch&quot; list, since she's funny and she's shown some good insight from her sales experience. I saw her having one conversation with McCrae that went something like this:<br />
<br />
Amanda: So Soandso came up to me to fight about some lingering slight from a few days ago.<br />
McCrae: You should have gone to her and apologized so the fight wouldn't have happened.<br />
Amanda: No. Her coming to me shows weakness to the house, that this is bothering her and she can't let go of it to get on with her game. It also makes her look disruptive, which puts a target on her back, and makes me a sympathetic victim, which can open the door to talking with a lot of people.<br />
<br />
That is pure &quot;A&quot; game right there, letting someone weak stew deliberately. I want to see how far Handy Mandy (her nickname since one night's activities with McCrae) can get in the game before production decides she's a threat to someone popular and gets her booted.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
